NYC Home Rental:Ownership

Visualising data about rental homes against home ownership numbers around Manhattan aiming to bring a sense of urgency and draw attention to volatility of the current market.

Context

Tools

  • Interaction Final, Spring 2023
  • VS Code
  • Figma
Your browser does not support Canvas element

This class coding project (final for the class) involved taking data from ↗NYC Open Data and analyzing it to identify a narrative & present it in an engaging manner. The objective was to demonstrate the huge invisible gap between home renting vs ownership trends in the current generation. Studies project that if you were not born before the 90s, you most probably won’t ever own your own house. I also aimed to highlight the difficulty of finding an apartment in NYC, emphasizing the stress and fast-paced nature of the process. Often, you save something to show your roommates, only to find out that it has already gone.

Since the project involved over 200 data points, it was crucial to design the system in a procedural and adaptive manner to accommodate the dataset's variety. The intention was to maintain a fluid design system that could easily accommodate to different data values, rather than being shoe-horned into a fixed style.

The bars in the visualization were designed with specific characteristics. The width of each bar was determined as a percentage value proportional to the number of available apartments in a particular building to remain honest to the scale of each than having it all be restricted to the width of the user’s viewport. On the other hand, the height of the bars was proportional to the square footage of the particular property. This choice aimed to translate the carpet area of an apartment space into a vertical scrolling website. The proximity of the bars was intentional, aiming to produce a claustrophobic feeling on the screen, mirroring the sense of overcrowding often experienced in a city like New York.

The information displayed within the bars was organized in a specific order. The ratio of rent versus owned properties was placed on the left side as it was considered the most important piece of information to convey. Following that, the address of each building was provided to remind visitors that these data points represent real locations that they could potentially visit, all of which was sourced from the publicly available data provided from the NYCopendata website.

Overview

Design Decisions

(or why the site looks like histograms on psychadelics)

The Bars

The Info

Color usage played a significant role in creating a stimulating and overwhelming visual experience, while still maintaining a refreshing palette for mundane statistic data. The harsh differentiation between gradients within each bar was derived from the rent-to-ownership ratio, with the left side representing rented properties and the right side representing owned properties.

The Colors

To ensure honest representation of the data, some bars were intentionally "ghosted" or greyed out. This was done when square footage data was missing, making it challenging to accurately determine the height of the bar. In these cases, the code was adjusted to assign a class that would give the bar a fixed and exaggeratedly small size, indicating the absence of complete information through color and scale.

Dealing with empty data points

The project also incorporated a "move" feature, allowing users to choose whether to experience the data in motion or navigate through the data themselves.

Animation

The choice of a black background was deliberate, aiming to create a visual environment where the main focus is on the data and information presented. This approach intended to evoke a feeling of being in an abyss, where all that exists are statistics about the housing market in NYC.

Background

In conclusion, this coding project aimed to visually capture the slippery nature of apartment hunting in NYC, utilizing design choices that created an engaging and claustrophobic experience. Through procedural and adaptive design elements, the project successfully presented over 200 data points in a stimulating and overwhelming yet informative manner, highlighting the challenges and realities of the housing market in the city.

Conclusion

Knowing what I know now, I would try and make the info more apparent and imperitive to read than a suggestion. From a coding point of view, it was definitely incredibly daunting to handle all this data but exploring and getting comfortable with different ways javascript could help me tackle this was extremely enlightening and humbling (as most coding projects are). We ended up using .JSON to collate the data and write a script and an HTML template for the JS to parse through the data and insert the values in the HTML and CSS like determining the height and width of each bar.

Initial Explorations

Goals

  • Represent the data accurately
  • Give a sense of scale & claustrophobia
  • Make the information bite-sized & digestable
  • Portray the data in visually stimulating manner, instead of a graph or pie chart


With these goals in mind, I presented this version to class and Nika, my professor, pointed out that while my approach was sound, the data could be misinterpreted as if all of the buildings were the same size. She encouraged me to explore options where a sense of scale and floors in the building were also taken into consideration.

This got my gears turning!

I was really fasinated by the design language OpenAI was using across their products, research and articles. I liked how each cover felt vague yet allowed me as a reader to derive my own relation between it and the topic it was about. I felt it was an appropriate way to communicate my data as the style was visually arresting yet abstract enough to not prescribe meaning

Conclusion + What I Would Do Differently

  • Working with like-minded individuals will never do any harm. I got to work closely with Ryan Carson, founder of ‘NO OD NY’, and interviewed him multiple times with questions and possible solutions. Alot of iteration was used in this project and I’m glad that it did.


  • Iteration and Reiteration. As this started as a project for a class in my first year of college, I had the benefit of running it by my peers. This turned out to be highly beneficial to the project as they pointed out things I wouldn't have considered otherwise.


  • Be cautious, but never assume. This project taught me to be incredibly sensitive with themes that deal with economic or social inequality, and bring as much empathy to the project as possible which is something I want to do in all of my designs. As I wasn’t directly in the user’s shoes, it was imperative that I understood who my user was and the nuances that needed to be considered when dealing with a topic like this.


  • First hand research is second to none. Although I was not able to collaborate with organizations aimed towards the same goal to the extent I desired, it turned into a riveting exercise to empathize with what it is like to be someone looking for but can’t find help without the first-hand interview.


  • More Analogue. I realized through feedback and more thought on making this drive even more accessible that this project would benefit having more information through analogue means than depending on its digital counterpart. The analogue and digital versions should stand parallel to each other than supplementary. Adding information about the nearest HRF, providing design services to HRFs to increase their reach or how to get to them would be some more useful information that could be put on the media.

Menu

Harm reduction is a real possibility, only that in the current climate, it doesn’t seem all that realistic. With questions about morality and practicality getting thwarted at the possibility of setting up a Harm Reduction Facility (HRF) or an Overdose Prevention Center (OPC), the hesitation must be met with trust and solutions based on safety and transparency.

This intervention takes the form of an interactive and scannable QR code that would be put up all around New York City in the form of stickers on the streets, posters in subway stations and shareable pamphlets with an aim to educate and generate awareness about the true impact of HRFs and the benefits that it can sustain on society. It aims to be a resource pool for immediate access to information about HRFs and OD prevention resources, from preventive steps to helping someone deal with their addiction and act as a virtual toolkit for those who need it the most.

Needle Drop

Handme: Product Listing Flow Case Study

Handme aims to easily connect students to buy & sell used products in a safe and trusted environment within their college community.

Responsibilities

Tools

  • User Experience (UX) Designer
  • Interaction (IxD) Designer
  • User Interface (UI) Designer
  • Brand Identity Designer
  • Brand Strategist
  • Product Designer
  • Figma
  • Miro
  • Jira
  • Adobe Photoshop
  • Adobe Illustrator
  • Adobe After Effects

Overview

Handme aims to easily connect students exclusively within their college community to buy & sell second-hand products in a safe and trusted environment.

This case study looks into my process designing the flow for listing a product on the platform.

Upon interviewing and surveying 22 people, I found that 85% of them were not likely to approach a second hand marketplace to sell items as they felt intimidated by the responsibilities of being an online seller.

For college students, with time always feeling like a limited resource, this made them feel like an avoidable commitment. In spite of this, there is a lack of an intuitive and user friendly way to list a product on an online marketplace.

How might we simplify the listing process to make it more approachable?

Problem

Solution

Context

Duration: 6 weeks

Outcome

  • Designed and shipped app MVP
  • Received an 9.8/10 rating from 90% users

How Might We

A few friends that study Computer Science across the US were thinking about developing a platform to solve this problem. When they brought this idea to me, I knew I was going to have a ball researching this topic and coming up with features to make sure the platform served these needs while being secure.

I was especially passionate since I understood that there was a place for an idea like this in the real world where I could have used something like this.

How I Got Here

I conducted thorough online research to study existing second-hand marketplaces, focusing on user experiences of the process of posting a listing. I looked at apps like Instagram (for its posting flow & marketplace capabilities), Offerup, Facebook Marketplace, Ebay & Depop.

I then evaluated the things that the industry incumbents had going for them and some things that could be improved or hadn’t been addressed:

Conclusion + What I'd Do Differently

Bigger Stronger Faster! This project was a major milestone, encompassing research to hand-off. It was a significant challenge, given the diverse student audience. Seeing my app on the App Store was both daunting and empowering. The project's scale heightened my diligence and mindfulness in making design choices.


Wearing the Developers’ Shoes. I constantly considered the developer's perspective, ensuring design brilliance aligned with practicality. This balancing act aimed for visionary yet feasible solutions.


Know Your Audience. Designing for a specific demographic was crucial. We opted for a non-traditional visual experience, with vibrant colors. This bold choice balanced usability and intuitive navigation, tailored for our target users.


Interview, Interview, Interview! Interviews were more than formality; they connected designs to user needs. The iterative process shaped the project and ensured user-centricity.


A Hands-On Approach. User testing during alpha and beta stages provided practical insights into design effectiveness. This hands-on approach, where theory met reality, reinforced the importance of user-centered design.
